<h4><span id="boot-fit">Boot fit</span>
</h4>
<p>Proper boot fit is crucial for your comfort and performance on the snowboard.</p>
<p>Snowboards boots should have a <b>snug fit</b>, which means that your toes should lightly touch the front of the inner liner when you stand straight. When you stand in the snowboard stance, your toes move backward a bit. Your heels should stay locked in place.</p>
<p>Don&rsquo;t forget to try out the boots in the socks you will use for riding. If your shop offers such option, have your boots <b>heat molded</b> after the purchase.</p>
<p>Check out the following guide for more information:</p>
<div>
<div class="c-embed c-embed--video"><iframe title="Snowboard Boot Fitting - An Essential Guide | Whitelines Snowboarding" width="500" height="281" src="about:blank" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen class=" lazyload" data-src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/GmAghXK5Ndc?feature=oembed"></iframe></div>
</div>
<p>If you&rsquo;re struggling with getting proper fitted boots you can also look for advice in <a href="https://www.snowboardingforum.com/boots/">Snowboarding Forum</a>.</p>
<h3><span id="bindings">Bindings</span>
</h3>
<div id="attachment_4895" class="wp-caption aligncenter">
<a href="https://unionbindingcompany.com/products/atlas?variant=29062812303465"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-4895" class="size-full wp-image-4895 lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==" alt="Union Atlas" width="780" height="650" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw== 1w" sizes="(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px" data-src="https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas.jpg" data-srcset="https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas.jpg 780w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas-765x638.jpg 765w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas-610x508.jpg 610w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas-460x383.jpg 460w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas-348x290.jpg 348w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/union-atlas-260x217.jpg 260w"></a><p id="caption-attachment-4895" class="wp-caption-text">An example of modern snowboard binding, <a href="https://unionbindingcompany.com/products/atlas?variant=29062812303465">Union Atlas</a></p>
</div>
<p>Similarly to snowboards, bindings are categorized according to their intended use to <b>all-mountain</b>, <b>freestyle</b> and <b>freeride </b>categories. Freestyle bindings are typically softer and freeride stiffer, with all-mountain category in between them.</p>
<div>
<div class="c-embed c-embed--video"><iframe title="How to choose snowboard bindings - Tactics" width="500" height="281" src="about:blank" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen class=" lazyload" data-src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/_1_-UChoS1E?feature=oembed"></iframe></div>
</div>
<p>Because snowboarding bindings translates movements from your boots to snowboard, they need to fit your boots well. The bindings are sold in different sizes (typically S/M, L/XL). Check the manufacturer sizing chart for the proper binding size for your boots.</p>
<p><i>Note: If you are buying <a href="https://www.burton.com">Burton</a> binding, be aware not to buy the EST version if you don&rsquo;t have a snowboard with the EST channel</i></p>
<p>The latest development in bindings technology is Burton&rsquo;s Step On, which removes the necessity of strapping in and off the bindings.</p>
<div id="attachment_4897" class="wp-caption aligncenter">
<a href="https://www.burton.com/us/en/step-on" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-4897" class="wp-image-4897 size-full lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==" alt="Burton Step On" width="780" height="439" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw== 1w" sizes="(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px" data-src="https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020.jpg" data-srcset="https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020.jpg 780w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020-765x431.jpg 765w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020-610x343.jpg 610w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020-460x259.jpg 460w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020-348x196.jpg 348w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/step-on-2020-260x146.jpg 260w"></a><p id="caption-attachment-4897" class="wp-caption-text"><a href="https://www.burton.com/us/en/step-on">Burton Step On</a> is a combination of strapless bindings and special boots.</p>
</div>
<h4><span id="binding-setup">Binding setup</span>
</h4>
<p>Setting up bindings means:</p>
<ul>
<li>customize binding so it fits your boot well (length of straps, etc.)</li>
<li>adjust your baseplate length so it creates good support for your boots&rsquo; sole (your boot should have some toe and heel overhang, but not too much)</li>
<li>mount it on your snowboard with your preferred angles and so your boots are centered over the board</li>
</ul>
