<h3><span id="snowboarding-etiquette">Snowboarding etiquette</span>
</h3>
<p>Snowboarders have earned a bad reputation among skiers over the years &ndash; they often see us as those who sit in the middle of the slope. Maybe you don&rsquo;t care what skiers think, but for your own safety and the safety of others, try to avoid doing this. If you need to stop, stop on the side of the track where other people can clearly see you. Never stop behind the lip or on places where others cannot see you.</p>
<div id="attachment_3595" class="wp-caption alignnone">
<img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-3595" class="size-full wp-image-3595 lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==" alt="" width="1024" height="683" data-src="https://www.xfivecdn.com/xfive/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/13164801/203227-unsplash.jpg"><p id="caption-attachment-3595" class="wp-caption-text">If you need to rest or adjust your gear, stop on the side of the track. Photo by&nbsp;<a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/SW4BTHmSGQg?utm_source=unsplash&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_content=creditCopyText">Ostap Senyuk</a>&nbsp;on&nbsp;<a href="https://unsplash.com/?utm_source=unsplash&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_content=creditCopyText">Unsplash</a></p>
</div>
<p>Get familiar with the rules valid for the resort when you are riding. Not only they will help you to ride more safely, it&rsquo;s good to know them when something happens and people start to argue about whose fault it was.</p>
<blockquote><p>Use your common sense and see beyond rules.</p></blockquote>
<p>It&rsquo;s a general rule that the skier or rider behind you is responsible for safely passing you. However, if you are doing wide open carving turns without looking uphill, you are asking for trouble. It&rsquo;s better to be safe than sorry &ndash; always look uphill when crossing the slope to avoid being hit by someone bombing down. It&rsquo;s easier to look uphill when you are on your toe edge, learn to quickly look over the shoulder when on the heel edge.</p>
<p>For more info check out <a href="https://snowboardingprofiles.com/what-are-the-basic-rules-of-snowboarding">What Are The Basic Rules Of Snowboarding?</a></p>
<h3><span id="how-to-teach-children-to-snowboard">How to teach children to snowboard</span>
</h3>
<p>Although you&rsquo;ve might seen YouTube videos of 2 or 3-year old children snowboarding, snowboarding is harder to grasp for an average child than skiing. While with skis a child can move their feet freely and only need to understand two relatively simple concepts (pizza / french fries), the sideways movement and balance involved in snowboarding is not that natural for small kids. This is partially because their centre of mass is moved towards the head until the age of 8.</p>
<p>Like with anything related to sports in small children, play and fun is the key. It&rsquo;s more about experience than technique. Children are not able to develop the same skills refinement as adults until the age of 12, anyway. As snowboarding represents one way load on the body, it&rsquo;s important to avoid overdoing it at a young age and devote enough time to compensation exercise or free play which best develops essential motor skills in children.</p>
<p>One way to safely experience mountains with your smaller children on a snowboard is using <a href="https://mdxone.com/">MDXONE snowboard harness</a> which is approved by CASI (Canadian Association of Snowboard Instructors).</p>
<div id="attachment_4866" class="wp-caption aligncenter">
<img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-4866" class="size-full wp-image-4866 lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==" alt="" width="780" height="468" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw== 1w" sizes="(max-width: 780px) 100vw, 780px" data-src="https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone.jpg" data-srcset="https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone.jpg 780w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone-765x459.jpg 765w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone-610x366.jpg 610w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone-460x276.jpg 460w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone-348x209.jpg 348w, https://www.xfive.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/mdxone-260x156.jpg 260w"><p id="caption-attachment-4866" class="wp-caption-text">With my then 5-years old son using MDXONE harness</p>
</div>
<p>Check out <a href="https://whitelines.com/snowboarding-advice/mini-shred-how-to-teach-your-kids-to-snowboard.html">How To Teach Your Kids To Snowboard</a> for more tips on how to snowboard with your children.</p>
<h2><span id="where-to-progress">Where to progress</span>
</h2>
<p>There are many areas to progress to after you master snowboarding basics. In this section we will describe the most common ones.</p>
<h3><span id="adaptive-stance">Adaptive stance</span>
</h3>
<p>Stance variations can confuse even more experienced riders. When you start snowboarding, you learn to ride in a neutral position, aligned with your snowboard. So why do some advanced snowboarders ride with their shoulders open?</p>
<p>In fact, such position allows you to ride with more speed and control. The following video shows the difference between a neutral and high speed position.</p>
<div>
<div class="c-embed c-embed--video"><iframe title="CASI Riding Tips: Anticipation / Separation" width="500" height="281" src="about:blank" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen class=" lazyload" data-src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/MrF45rdEGG8?feature=oembed"></iframe></div>
</div>
<p><a href="https://www.nzsia.org/snowboard/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBINZ</a> defines <a href="https://vimeo.com/293472666" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">stance scale</a> with three levels:</p>
<ul>
<li>basic</li>
<li>active</li>
<li>high performance stance</li>
</ul>
<p>Master all three of them and adapt your stance depending on the conditions and your riding style. The following videos teach how to do toe and heel side turns using high performance stance.</p>
